distributions.description: Enables to list data items contained in the episode (dataset) as ‘Catalog', 'Seismic Network', 'Event related waveforms', 'Velocity model' and some 'Industrial data', features filtering. Episode comprehensively describes a geophysical process induced or triggered by human technological activity, which could pose a hazard for populations, infrastructure and environment. This episode describes seismic monitoring of the initial stage of wastewater injection into a disposal well of the Val d'Agri oil field. The monitoring unraveled a low magnitude swarm induced by disposal operations that initiated just a few hours after the beginning of injection. Main objective is to provide seismic data to be analyzed with advanced techniques for a better understanding of the mechanisms of injection-linked seismicity and of physical properties of the reservoir.
distributions.title: Episode VAL D'AGRI FIELD: conventional hydrocarbon extraction - dataset

distributions.description: The World Magnetic Model is the standard model used by the U.S. Department of Defense, the U.K. Ministry of Defence, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and the International Hydrographic Organization (IHO), for navigation, attitude and heading referencing systems using the geomagnetic field. It is also used widely in civilian navigation and heading systems. The model is produced at 5-year intervals, with the current model expiring on December 31, 2024. Irregular changes in the Earth’s core field limit the lifetime of any predictive model such as the WMM.
distributions.title: World Magnetic Model (WMM)

distributions.description: The International Geomagnetic Reference Field (IGRF) is released by the International Association of Geomagnetism and Aeronomy (IAGA). It consists of a standard mathematical description of the Earth's main magnetic field that is used widely in studies of the Earth's deep interior, its crust and its ionosphere and magnetosphere. The current generation of the model is number 12, revisions are made approximately every 5 years. The coefficients for the recent degree and order 13 main field constituent models were finalized by a task force of IAGA in December 2019. The IGRF is the product of a collaborative effort between magnetic field modellers and the institutes involved in collecting and disseminating magnetic field data from satellites and from observatories and surveys around the world.
distributions.title: International Geomagnetic Reference Field (IGRF), global model

distributions.description: Data from multi-scale research into the physical behavior of Earth materials, including rock mechanics experiments, fluid flow tests and petrophysical analyses, performed under crustal or upper mantle conditions of stress, temperature and chemistry. Materials typically studied include sedimentary rocks, like sandstone, limestone, coal and evaporites like rock salt and gypsum, igneous or volcanic rocks like granite, basalt and gabbro, metamorphic rocks like marble and schist, and anthropogenic composites like cement, or 3D-printed rock. The data provide key information into the processes governing geohazards, whether human induced or natural, including earthquakes, land subsidence, landslides and volcanic activity. As such, these data are frequently used in models and upscaling studies, aimed at understanding system-scale Earth behavior and at steering strategy for safe and sustainable use of our subsurface.
distributions.title: Data on rock and melt physical properties

distributions.description: Collection of Atmospheric Phase Screen (APS) maps generated from global atmospheric model. APS product represents a map of the atmospheric phase delay (in rad) of an interferogram corresponding to the difference of atmospheric phase delay maps between the two dates of the interferogram (newest minus oldest) computed from a global atmospheric model (the name of the model is given in the metadata). APS file format is a two bands geoTIFF: band 1 is the atmospheric phase delay of the interferogram (in rad), positive away from satellite; band 2 is a shaded view of the topography (simulated SAR amplitude image from the DEM). Further product specifications, naming convention, and metadata are described in the TCS SATD Product Description document (https://gitlab.com/epos-tcs-satdata/doc).
distributions.title: Interferogram Atmospheric Phase Screen from Global Atmospheric Model

distributions.description: Collection of geocoded Unwrapped Interferograms (InU) generated worldwide by exploiting Copernicus Sentinel-1 data. InU are generated by the systematic and on-demand processing services of TCS partners. The Unwrapped Interferogram product represents a map of the full evolution of the phase difference (i.e. not restricted in the -pi,pi domain) computed between two Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) images acquired over the same scene from (possibly) the same position. The Unwrapped Interferogram is linearly related to the Line of Sight (LOS) projection of the actual Earth’s surface displacement that occurred between the two acquisitions involved in the Interferogram generation. InU are provided in geoTIFF format. InU product contains the actual (floating point) geocoded ground displacement (i.e. the phase difference converted in centimeters) between the two SAR data involved in the interferogram generation. Further product specifications, naming convention, and metadata are described in the TCS SATD Product Description document (https://gitlab.com/epos-tcs-satdata/doc).
distributions.title: Unwrapped Interferograms

distributions.description: The European Fault-Source Model 2020 (EFSM20) was compiled in the framework of the EU Project SERA, Work Package 25, JRA3. EFSM20 includes only faults that are deemed to be capable of generating earthquakes of magnitude equal to or larger than 5.5 and aims at ensuring a homogenous input for use in ground-shaking hazard assessment in the Euro-Mediterranean area, namely the European Seismic Hazard Model 2020 (ESHM20). This is the standard OGC WFS web service providing the European Fault Source Model 2020 (EFSM20) data related to subduction zones in the form of vectors. Layers description: 1) efsm20_slabdepths: Depth isolines (contours) representing the geometry of the top surface of the slab. Polylines. 2) efsm20_si_parameters: Subduction Interface (SI) parameters. Polygons encompassing the SI area in map view. 3) efsm20_si_discretization: Subduction Interface (SI) discretized in areas spanning 1 km depth. Polygons encompassing each area in map view. 4) efsm20_si_realizations: Subduction Interface (SI) model realizations considering uncertainties. Polygons encompassing each area of the different realizations in map view. 5) efsm20_is_lattice: Intraslab (IS) model constituted by equally-spaced nodes sampling the crustal part of the slab volume. Points. The full description of all the parameters can be found in the documentation linked below. This service is hosted and maintained by Istituto Nazionale di Geofisica e Vulcanologia (INGV) through the European Databases of Seismogenic Faults (Seismofaults.eu) installation.
distributions.title: European Fault Source Model 2020 - Subduction (OGC WFS)

distributions.description: NOTICE. This dataset is obsolete and remains available to allow users to reproduce previous studies or experiments. For new studies, users are encouraged to use EFSM20 (https://doi.org/10.13127/efsm20), which superseded EDSF13.The European Database of Seismogenic Faults 2013 (EDSF13) was compiled in the framework of the EU Project SHARE, Work Package 3, Task 3.2. EDSF13 includes only faults that are deemed to be capable of generating earthquakes of magnitude equal to or larger than 5.5 and aims at ensuring a homogeneous input for use in ground-shaking hazard assessment in the Euro-Mediterranean area. Several research institutions participated in this effort with the contribution of many scientists (see the Documentation reported in the DOI landing page for a full list). The standard OGC WFS web service provides the European Database of Seismogenic Faults 2013 (EDSF13) crustal fault data as geographical features and attributes. It covers approximately the European area. This service is hosted and maintained by `Istituto Nazionale di Geofisica e Vulcanologia (INGV).
distributions.title: European Database of Seismogenic Faults - Crustal Faults (OGC WFS)

distributions.description: OGC compliant for WFS (1.0.0, 2.0.0) for map layers of the ESHM20 unified earthquake catalogue. The ESHM20 unified earthquake catalogue consists of two parts: the so-called “instrumental” catalogue (after 1900) based on the updated European-Mediterranean Earthquake Catalogue (EMEC,  Grünthal, G., Wahlström, et al.2012), the European PreInstrumental Earthquake Catalogue EPICA (Rovida and Antonucci, 2021;) earthquake catalogue (between the years 1000 CE and 1899 CE).

distributions.description: The Euro-Mediterranean Submarine landSlide database (EMSS21) displays information collected from both the literature and geophysical records. Data from the literature is collected from georeferenced map figures, from which the outline of the landslide deposit and the landslide scar have been digitized. Most information such as age, volume, typology, inferred trigger mechanism and relationship to fluid flow features and metadata is extracted from the relevant article. Area of the deposit and landslide runout is determined from the digitized polygons and polylines, volume (if not available) is determined from area and mean thickness. If the latter is not available, the volume is determined from the Area-Volume relationship for landslides where volume has already been determined. When the dat originates directly from geophysical records the outline and scars have been determined from geomorphological interpretation of swath bathymetric maps and interpretation of submarine landslides on a variety of seismic records. In such instances, age information originates from a variety of methods presenting a wide range of accuracies, from radiometric dating to well-seismic correlation as well as ages inferred from mean sedimentation rates. In many instances, landslides identified in the literature are dated with an age epoch only.
